Getting Started
This guide provides the initial steps to set up a new Discord bot project using our framework.
Prerequisites
Before you begin, ensure you have the following requirements met:
A code editor (Visual Studio Code is recommended).
Node.js v20.11 or higher (or Bun).
Basic knowledge of programming logic.
Basic knowledge of JavaScript and TypeScript.
Basic knowledge of the discord.js library.
Scaffolding a New Project
You can use our Command Line Interface (CLI) to quickly set up a new Discord bot project.
Create a new folder for your project and open it in your terminal.
Run the command below using your preferred package manager to launch the CLI:
# Using npx (Node.js)
npx constatic@latest

# Using Bun
bunx constatic@latest

# Using Yarn
yarn dlx constatic@latest

# Using pnpm
pnpm dlx constatic@latest

Use code with caution.
Sh
Select the first option: Start a new Discord bot project.
The CLI will then ask you a few questions to set up your project:
Project name (the path to the folder)
Database (optional)
Extra features (optional)
Install dependencies (optional)
After answering the prompts, your project will be generated and ready for you to start developing.
Project Configuration
With the project generated, follow these steps to get your bot online.
Open the .env file located in the root of your project directory.
Add your bot's token to this file.
For instructions on how to create a bot application and get a token, please visit the Discord Developer Portal.
BOT_TOKEN=your_token_here
Use code with caution.
Dotenv
After setting the token, you can run the project in development mode with the following command:
npm run dev
Use code with caution.
Sh
Your bot should now be online, and you can start developing your features
